RIYADH: The world's Muslims will mark the first day of Ramadan on Saturday after an official sighting of the new crescent moon, the Saudi Supreme Court announced on Friday. This will be the first year since 2019 that Ramadan in Saudi Arabia will be observed without coronavirus restrictions. The Supreme Court also congratulated the Custodian of the Two Holy Mosques King Salman, Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman, all citizens and residents of the Kingdom and all Muslims on the holy month, Saudi Press Agency reported. #PHOTOS: Images from @arabnews correspondent on the ground with moon-sighting committee as #Ramadan2022 is announced to start on Saturday https://t.co/TsxOr4f7fc pic.twitter.com/ickIon8Nl2 — Arab News (@arabnews) April 1, 2022  